### File Descriptions
- **app.py**  
  The main backend Python application file. It handles routing for all nine pages, processes data from local text files in the `data/` directory, manages reading and writing operations for articles, bookmarks, comments, and trending data, and serves the HTML templates with the appropriate data. Since the application is not very complex, consolidating backend logic into this single file simplifies maintenance and deployment.

- **templates/**  
  Directory containing all HTML template files for the web application pages, each corresponding to one of the nine pages specified in the requirements. These templates include the defined elements with their respective IDs and are rendered by `app.py`.

  - `dashboard.html` — Dashboard Page  
  - `article_catalog.html` — Article Catalog Page  
  - `article_details.html` — Article Details Page  
  - `bookmarks.html` — Bookmarks Page  
  - `comments.html` — Comments Page  
  - `write_comment.html` — Write Comment Page  
  - `trending.html` — Trending Articles Page  
  - `category.html` — Category Page  
  - `search_results.html` — Search Results Page  

- **static/**  
  Contains static assets such as CSS and JavaScript files to style the pages and add client-side interactivity.

  - `css/styles.css` — Stylesheet for consistent styling across all pages.  
  - `js/scripts.js` — JavaScript file for handling UI behaviors like button clicks and dynamic content updates.

- **data/**  
  Directory holding all local text files used for data storage as per the requirements. These files are read and updated by the backend to manage articles, categories, bookmarks, comments, and trending information.

  - `articles.txt` — Stores article data.  
  - `categories.txt` — Stores category data.  
  - `bookmarks.txt` — Stores bookmarked articles data.  
  - `comments.txt` — Stores comments on articles.  
  - `trending.txt` — Stores trending articles data.  

This structure cleanly separates backend logic, frontend templates, static resources, and data storage, aligning well with the project requirements and facilitating straightforward development and maintenance."

